✅ What happens if getServerSideProps throws an error in Next.js?
If getServerSideProps throws an error, Next.js treats it as a server error and renders the error page. By default, the user will see a 500 Internal Server Error page, either the built‑in one or a custom error page if you’ve defined it.

🔹 Default Behavior
1️⃣ Unhandled Error
If an error is thrown and not handled, Next.js will:
	• Return HTTP 500
	• Render: 
		○ pages/500.js (if present), or
		○ the default Next.js 500 error page
	• Log the error on the server console

export async function getServerSideProps() {
  throw new Error("Database failed");
}
✅ Result: 500 error page shown to the user

🔹 How to Handle Errors Properly (Recommended)
✅ 1️⃣ Use try/catch inside getServerSideProps
This prevents crashing the page and gives you control over UX.

export async function getServerSideProps() {
  try {
    const data = await fetchData();
    return { props: { data } };
  } catch (error) {
    return { props: { error: true } };
  }
}
``
✅ Page still renders
✅ Error handled gracefully

✅ 2️⃣ Redirect on Error
Useful when data is mandatory.

catch (error) {
  return {
    redirect: {
      destination: "/error",
      permanent: false,
    },
  };
}
✅ Better user experience
✅ No broken page

✅ 3️⃣ Show 404 if Data Is Missing
If the resource doesn’t exist:

if (!data) {
  return { notFound: true };
}
✅ Renders 404.js
✅ Appropriate for missing resources

🔹 Custom Error Pages
You can define:
	• pages/500.js → Server errors
	• pages/_error.js → Unified error handling (advanced)

// pages/500.js
export default function Custom500() {
  return <h1>Something went wrong</h1>;
}

🔄 What About Client‑Side Navigation?
	• During client‑side transitions, an error in getServerSideProps: 
		○ Redirects to the error page
		○ Still triggers a full page reload

⚠️ Important Notes (Interview‑Relevant)
	• Errors in getServerSideProps are server‑side only
	• Users never see stack traces in production
	• Logging + monitoring (Datadog, New Relic, App Insights) is critical
	• Never expose sensitive error details to the UI

🧠 Interview‑Ready 30‑Second Answer
	If getServerSideProps throws an error, Next.js returns a 500 server error and renders the default or custom 500 error page.
	To avoid breaking the user experience, we usually handle errors using try/catch and return fallback props, a redirect, or notFound.
	This gives us better control over error handling and improves reliability in production.

✅ Real‑World Example (Enterprise / Cognizant‑Style)
	• API timeout → show friendly error message
	• Auth failure → redirect to login
	• Missing data → return 404
	• Unexpected exception → log + show 500 page

